Duel to the last blood: MP3 players against mobile phones
We will advise how to choose
While almost every mobile phone can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can call.
This makes it clear that it is best to buy only the phone.
However, there are many reasons to get an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the way of use and the needs of the future owner.
Perhaps you would hardly buy an expensive high-quality turntable to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album.
First of all these musical products do not come out as LP and from a qualitative point of view for this there is not even an objective reason.
If, however, hard-rock, jazz or blues vinyls are crowded on your shelves, you probably dream of a turntable like this.
It also works with portable music, i.e. compressed music or simply in MP3 format.
Here too there are the price and quality categories.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend 8,000 crowns for a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan may hardly digest the twenty-crown headphones of the market.
Two extremes between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
It is the life of the batteries that decides.
Some high-quality music players can do a lot more than just read music, but cell phones don’t do it by accident.
There is no other device as universal as the mobile phone.
Next to the primary functions, phone and text, it can read music and videos, record both and has a camera, sometimes better sometimes worse and maybe even can navigate.
And if we consider smartphones and handhelds, you will also have a miniature computer in your pocket.
It is a small miracle that no refrigerator can grill and no television can photograph anything.
The universality of mobile phones also brings disadvantages.
The more functions you use on the mobile and the sooner the indicator on the screen will require the charger.
Reading music consumes a lot of energy.
Few cell phones can read music for more than twelve hours, usually, and much less.
In this sense, music players (especially the simplest ones) are much more effective.
As for cheap cell phones, don’t count on them to last for more than a few hours.
If you still add, from time to time, some calls, get to work for safety another charger, this applies even to the most expensive appliances.
But you won’t have this problem with an MP3 player, even the worst ones last at least 9 hours at continuous functionality on a charge.
An additional problem exists when downloading music to your mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have the universal USB port and not all of them can be connected to the computer without special software.
Of course the music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but only a few memory readers are able to do without an adapter for minicards that are not used in mobile phones.
Readers, except for a few exceptions (iPod) do not need any special software.
Just fill the device with music via USB from your computer.
Most mobile phones and players create a media library by themselves, sorted by performers' names, album name, genre, or user classification.
Some devices only reproduce the tree structure of folders, similar to the Explorer tool in Windows, and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobile phones can do more.
When you choose a particular device, you are mainly interested in the battery strength, memory capacity, quality and type of audio outputs and clearly the ease of use.
If you use music mainly as a background and if you listen to it every day only briefly on the tram, you only need a mobile phone that reads MP3.
This is now possible on any mobile phone.
You don’t have to worry too much about which formats your phone or reader recognizes.
MP3 players support them all, the majority of the global music that comes to them will be in this format.
In addition to this format that belongs to the most popular, the total majority of devices support music in WMA format.
There is less AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPods).
The best mobile phones also allow, for example, to buy music online.
Just visit, through the mobile internet network, the corresponding pages of the operator (or another provider) and buy the song or album.
This same service could already be a valid argument for buying a mobile-reader.
Unfortunately the offer of the operators is poor and is limited, usually, only to hits of the moment of the radio.
The prices are not very low.
But it is generally assumed that this very way of selling music (either via GSM, internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their cell phones behind them.
Anyone who wants to listen to a little something peeks in their pocket while the MP3 player is forgotten at home.
However, it also depends on this, if you always carry behind the headphones or at least the wireless headset.
If not, you can use the built-in player that almost every mobile phone, but only a small portion of MP3 players, has.
Perhaps the biggest advantage of mobile-readers will be, for many, the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than 3,000 kroner.
For 3 and 4 thousand crowns you will already buy a very dignified walkman.
Usually, however, you will be limited by the absence of an entrance for the common headphones.
The best and technically most equipped mobile phones and also with the 3.5 mm socket for common headphones, cost up to 15,000 crowns.
But the advantage of the readers is, in addition to others, the easy handling.
The simplest ones are not necessarily cheaper (see our choice) and anyone can really handle them.
The minimum of functions, the similarity of handling once with the common stereo or perhaps the turntable, is obvious.
There is no danger of accidentally bumping into the start-up of the mobile internet and consequently a giant bill for data transmission.
Which Appliance to Take
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (such as M2, microSD, etc.).
Also with regard to the purchase of the respective card, you fall into the 2,000 crowns.
But be careful.
The basic models support only cards with the maximum capacity of 2GB.
Only the most expensive ones can do it even with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and want to buy an inexpensive MP3 player, take Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB) you do not have to spend more than 1 100 crowns.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners, take the specialized mobile phones - walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have individual keys for MP3 and the convenience of the service so it comes close to the same MP3 player.
In this area Sony Ericsson has made more way, which phones of the line walkman have the same scale of use as MP3 players sold separately.
MP3 players from the above brands ensure the same service and price range up to 4,000 kroner, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, typically up to 35 hours).
The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic as early as this year.
Possibly.
Perhaps the mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer virtually all services like their partners in Western Europe.
Here, however, something is missing – a virtual operator that forces the traditional ones to lower the price.
Maybe he won't be missing for long.
Of the fact that Czech operators belong to the most expensive in Europe we have already written many times on Mobil.cz.
In the end, <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> also confirmed this, pointing out that the price of SMS is higher in us than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of the regularisation of roaming charges, perhaps a paradoxical situation will arise - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high in relation to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really want to start the fight.
Maybe it sounds absurd, even here we have three mobile networks and coverage highly above 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense he also often emphasizes the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>) , Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, who in the past has sometimes expressed that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with its own network no longer has many possibilities. (Also perhaps it would be difficult now to find other frequencies).
But there is still another possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry into the market of virtual operators has led to a significant lowering of prices, to which then the traditional operators should have reacted.
At the same time, even before sharks such as Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile entered the market, similar rumours resonated in Britain as we did.
However, it has been shown that there is a place for such operators and that they can be really successful.
In the end, we do not have to go very far for examples.
In February of this year we informed you of the arrival of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year this operator has managed to win over 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, to which in the Czech Republic it belongs, among other things, U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
To be able to function effectively, that is, they need far fewer customers than a traditional operator.
They do not carry behind,that is, relatively high expenses for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world virtual operators usually come at low cost, offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often in balance with the offer of services more restricted
So for example Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers SMS that cost at least half as much as its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows can be a pretty good move even betting on a target group not a small one.
This operator so to speak focuses specifically on men.
"Real men choose Mobilking operator they like and can trust," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company that produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether we can affirm a similar concept as in Poland.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD>, a spokesman for Vodafone, said: “The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators rely.
In addition from the point of view of services is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic no possibility, say mobile network operators
But it seems almost certain that if there will ever be an operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
"There is talk of the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not have many expectations.
The ignition of Mobilking will take place rather in the other countries of our area," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, the press spokeswoman of the financial group Penta, told Mobile.cz in a telephone dialogue.
Thus he indirectly confirmed that the current operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not very supportive of this thinking.
Rather, they try to do everything so that no potential competitors are created.
For some time he has not hidden his interest in the launch of a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group, which would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefonica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We have a great interest in being able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunication services.
And the sooner the better.
We have negotiated repeatedly on this possibility with all Czech mobile network operators.
We have already made progress in negotiations with some of them," said Pavel Kaidl, spokesman for the group.
So maybe better times will come.
Unofficial information indicates that the first virtual operator will have to have it perhaps by the end of the year.
For now, however, around his creation stands an impenetrable wall of silence.
“At the moment we do not believe that there is room in the Czech market for the creation of a fully-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far no subject with a complex and serious project has turned to us," mentioned in his statement to Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> of the press section of Telef<0xC3><0xB2>nika O2.
The specificity of the Czech market is also used by the other operators.
T-Mobil press spokeswoman Martina Kemrová adds in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "For now we have not noticed any vital and beneficial commercial project for both, on which it is possible to continue to build."
“In the T-Mobil network, it is unlikely that a virtual operator will appear by the end of the year.
At this point we should have had a concrete agreement on the table, so that it could be considered on the horizon.”
Vodafone focuses its attention rather on meeting its 3G licensing requirements.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: “We are open to the negotiations of potential virtual operators and this especially in the context of sharing of expenses and infrastructure.
We consider this, from the point of view of the customers, the most productive.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet.”
Competent authorities -with complicit operators
The attitude of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to lower prices and thus to a decrease in profit.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The annoyances around the U:fon creation testify that when operators care about one thing they know how to row on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure was on <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> during the period of U:fon's creation towards the T-Mobile company.
This is evidenced by publicly accessible information from <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>’s web pages.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument for not accepting the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has only recently been enhanced after all with the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Regarding the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would place high demands on him and above all on his services."
The attitude of mobile operators is surprising, however, the complete disinterest on the part of the Czech regulatory bodies.
It is not just the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> which unfortunately in the Czech Republic – unlike Britain and other developed countries – has no competence to interfere in economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
This, however, in relation to the whole problem has taken its typical position.
"The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of the contract for the rental of the necessary infrastructure between the mobile operator and the virtual operator.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the bid from potential buyers has probably not been interesting enough for traditional operators," said Kristián Chalupa of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS External Relations Section in response to our question.
Such a statement by the representatives of the operators is perhaps not surprising.
Instead, the office has to defend the interests of consumers and, moreover, ensure that no one takes advantage of its position in the market, it is more than a delicate affair.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Overseas where virtual operators commonly operate, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile services."
But of course the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices do not belong to the interests of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
Truly shocking in the whole situation is the almost thrilling harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence arises on its own.
Just as the identical price of gasoline for all gas stations is undoubtedly the result of coincidence and competition.
"The section has found no signs of anti-competitive behaviour regarding this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position, so it does not have a corresponding greater responsibility for its behavior in the market.
The necessary tools for the opening up of the mobile network market for virtual operators may also be lacking in the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa mentioned in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many points of controversy.
Of course, there is the analysis of relevant markets by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of economic competition the only market.
In such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach - the agreement of the network operator is always necessary for the creation of a virtual operator.
And the mobile operator has – after all, logically – the monopoly of its network.
So for a certain portion it must be dominant.
But even if we do not admit this argument, for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS it should be a minimum of alarming that three mobile operators proceed in such a strangely similar way.
At the same time, complaints from the parties concerned (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that during negotiations with all operators they encounter very similar obstacles.
Discharging responsibility to <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick with which <0xC3><0x9A>OHS keeps itself out of the whole affair.
We have already seen this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it was not possible to promote the expansion of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>'s rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the recently approved update of the telecommunications law, despite the fact that many experts expected the situation to improve.
This fact the representatives of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS must know more than well, but perhaps their interests are elsewhere.
It can be done, when no one looks
Unbeknownst to us, the operation of these pseudo-virtual operators, some of which even exist in Czech mobile networks, remains.
These are companies that publish their own mobile phone service price lists, but they are only partially public.
These are usually companies that deal with multilevel marketing.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only pre-established people.
The magic lies in the fact that the company vis-à-vis the operator appears as a classic corporate customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer then receives special price offers (and more).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a pre-sale.
“If the cases you are talking about, which we will be interested in, are presented, it could be a violation of the contractual conditions, and it could result in the conclusion of the cooperation with that company,” Martina Kemrová replied to the question in question.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity would not reach the ears of those responsible for mobile operators.
Especially in the cases of the 3 companies mentioned can be thousands of customers.
No operator defends himself at the same time from such an attitude.
From the activity of these companies they derive a profit that is not indifferent and at the same time - unlike real virtual operators - they are not harmed in any way with their official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> warns of possible problems: "The law allows for similar speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it as regular customers of mobile operators.
But just that should be a strange minimum at <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
In addition, another issue opens up for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an attitude, why are they blocking the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has rights strong enough to expose similar activities and if it does not want to, it will not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the operators who have no idea of everything and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we are no longer expensive
As the text has already been said several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a significant reduction in prices for services.
At the same time, in virtually all countries where operators were born, traditional operators were more or less trying to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were practically identical - market too small, at the limit too saturated, problems with the quality of services etc.
But in developed countries precisely in these cases have intervened the regulatory bodies to defend not the mobile operators but their customers.
Both with formal measures and with non-formal pressure, then we came to the creation of the first virtual operator and to him others were attached.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies throw themselves from one to the other like a boiling potato.
From our experience we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of skills in these cases makes him more than comfortable.
But let's not throw in the towel.
If the behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator will really appear soon from us, the Czech mobile market will get back on track.
If one of the operators had consented to the creation of a virtual mobile operator only <0xC3><0x9A>OHS could hardly remain impassible to the refusal (discrimination) of the other interested parties.
And maybe we will stop calling at higher prices than the rest of Europe.
