The bilingual debate: immersion in English
In this episode of Educational Look, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the candidates' position on bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, senior member in California Studies and senior director of educational studies at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is the co-author of the book “Not as Good as You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs to Choose a School.”
Really attracting Hispanic voters is a complicated business.
Barack Obama’s educational projects are a significant example.
Mr. Obama’s campaign notes that, “African-American and Latino students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students,” which is true.
To combat these shortcomings in achieving goals, Obama’s educational plan specifically supports, among other things, “transitional bilingual education” for English learners.
Yet the question for Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes classroom teaching of languages other than English, does not take into account his interest in bridging learning gaps.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, an elementary school in eastern Los Angeles County.
The school’s students are mostly Hispanic and low-income.
More than a third of students, many of whom have recently arrived, are studying English.
But, among fourth graders, an astonishing 100 percent of students took the upper-level test in the 2008 state math exam.
An equally surprising 93 percent of fourth graders took the expert-level test on art-of-language-English.
This incredible result was achieved using a different ingredient from Mr. Obama’s favorite.
Sixth Street emphasizes reviewing and exercising, constant assessment of skills, and a “no apology” attitude.
Also, and this is where Mr. Obama should take note, according to Linda Mikels, director of Sixth Street, the school’s obstructive approach to English learners is “full immersion.”
The use of English emphasizes the almost exclusive use of English in the context of education.
Ms. Mikels, who opposes bilingual education, told me, "We had a fantastic success with a student just coming from Mexico and if you had entered the class 12 months later you wouldn't have been able to pinpoint what it was."
"It works," he noted, "for us it works."
Would Obama model a school like Sixth Street Prep to replicate it in other Spanish-majority schools with English students?
The results achieved by the school make the answer to that question very easy, but the educational policy in its own party (the National Education Associations is a longtime supporter of bilingual education) and its own continued support for bilingual education prevent it from predicting Mr. Obama’s answer.
While he agrees that immigrants should study English, Obama recently made the argument trivial when he said people should stop worrying about “English-only” legislation.
Instead, he said, "you have to make sure your children are able to speak Spanish."
If Obama really wants to close these gaps in achievement, he should carefully consider the educational models that work rather than scorning or trivializing them.
