In a city apart, pride and processes of a black life
Tucked away in the expansive theme park on the outskirts of Orlando, a few miles from the splendor, the noise, the enormous, lies the quiet city where the pride and complications of the African-American experience come into life.
Eatonville, the first all-black incorporated city in the country and the birthplace of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as it was described in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet fields, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guava, two schools and no prison."
It is now a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to show their respect for Hurston, the most famous writer of Harlem Renaissance.
Yet in many ways, the city he described – and which makes tourists stop by including it in the Florida tour guide produced by the Depression-era Federal Writers’ Project – remains a place apart.
She is as independent, dignified, and private as she was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their thoughts with the white man, that “knowing so little about us, he doesn’t know what he’s missing.”
Even now, in a year when a black presidential nominee, Senator Barack Obama, has been called in for an opening speech on race, many here remain suspicious of the outsider’s gaze.
“We’re very cautious about how our story is told,” said Hortense Jones, 59, a lifelong resident and member of the city’s oldest church.
"It must be right."
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and difficulty.
It is both a historical model of black power grab and a community of nearly 2,400 where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a literary center but also an example in the shadow of the oaks of the rural culture of the blacks of the south - sometimes disdained, sometimes rewarded - born of American slavery.
Not surprisingly, the residents here are both proud and protective.
And the concern for Eatonville's image really began with Zora, who everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced the world to her hometown through sincere, dialect-rich books such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs of the Florida guide transformed the city, just outside Rout 17, a road that runs through often-forgotten central Florida into a backdrop of black history and human drama.
Low as a crate in both life and literature, Hurston took readers to the store owned by Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then diverted to more private areas.
"Out of the street on the left," he wrote, "is the modern public school, brown with the white trim, with its well-kept gardens and courtyards, which Howard Miller always cared about, thinking he could just read and write."
She also mentioned Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and whatever fits the passing rooms".
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville with self-government but also with illiteracy, second marriage and sex.
Obviously this was not Fodor's.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone appreciated.
“Zora used to say it the way it was,” said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of Johnson’s girls Hurston immortalizes by quoting men singing rude songs about their beauty.
He adds, “Some people don’t like it.”
Hurston is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who frequently returned from her family and moved to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalls that when Hurston plunged into the city, he usually arrived unannounced in a triumphant Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants in a city that still boasts decent clothing today.
Many of the inhabitants were fascinated, says Mr. Franklin, while others grinned.
"People were always very happy to see Zora," said Mr. Franklin.
But, he added, swinging on his back patio chair overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "she never stayed long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of print.
Along with the rest of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Fla., where she had lived.
In Eatonville, there were no great commemorative ceremonies, and no great conferences.
"I don't think they understand his contribution to the world or his legacy at all," said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows," a 2003 biography of Hurston.
A change took place in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted to place a five-lane highway across the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the two-lane main road.
Orlando’s expansion has already pushed Interstate 4 through the city’s western boundary.
The proposal came when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had brought an end to its idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the battle over racial mixing brought hatred to the community's doorstep.
"During that time, a group of white boys came and threw oranges and stuff at the people sitting on the side," says Mr. Franklin.
“We actually had a girl who was killed by that one time.
They threw a watermelon out of a car."
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston made a request to the Supreme Court for forced integration, calling his decision in Brown against the school office "an insult rather than an honor to my race".
Residents now say that the desegregation of schools, although positive in some respects, dilutes Eatonville’s cohesion and jeopardizes the confidence of its young people.
“Black kids were used to being hugged — I remember this — you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening,” said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and the executive director of Preserve the Eatonville Community, a nonprofit group.
This lasted, he added, until the teachers and students came from the same place.
"You didn't hug your white teacher because your white teacher...- I mean, there's a cultural division there," Ms. Nathiri said.
Civil rights, however, helped and made room for many more Zora Neale Hurstons - black writer, actress and artist who overcame prejudices, as she did, with cheerful self-confidence and lines like: "How can some deny themselves the pleasure of my company!
I just can't understand."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker began a long journey to the unmarked tomb of Hurston and began to fight for the resurrection of her reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed biography on Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway hit the shelves of bookstores, reintroducing it into the American canon.
The highway project came just as his most famous daughter had turned the spotlight again.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began designing a festival dedicated to Hurston in 1988 to show what could ruin the state with its highway.
Thousands of fans came to the inaugural event two years later, and every January, many return for the commemoration.
Many years later, the state pulled back from its street project.
"The five lanes of the resurrected highway brought what would be called high speed, a real pride for the city," Ms. Nathiri said.
Mrs. Boyd puts it simpler: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory over the highway project helped to change the image that the city has of itself.
Those from outside the city like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who started coming to church here in 1993, began to appear in large numbers, and residents began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville was added to the public historical register in 1998.
A new single-storey bookstore (named Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on a repaved and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can give the feeling of a side road in the summer rain, as small as when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1980s.
(It's 90 percent black today.)
Outsiders who come to search for the Eatonville story, for its meaning, are often still treated with caution.
A permission request in advance is required for most of the interviews, to some things - such as the murals on the oldest church in Eatonville, painted by a white man, which show black men in the fields - are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, such as Ms. Jones, a chubby teacher, with a penchant for bright red, still fears that their island community will be misunderstood.
Yet, as the Hurston festival expanded, a high level of city pride also emerged.
Young people, in particular, tend to see Eatonville with Hurston seeing his entire race: beautiful, troubled, and everything, no better, no worse and proud, creative, hardworking, silly and confused like other races and ethnic groups in America.
It is sincere civic affection that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin’s nephew, Edwin Harvey, 18, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the local government or for the Police Department, who he said may need help.
And even those who are younger, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
“A lot of people, if they’ve just come in here, will think, ‘Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,’” said Alondra Kenon after Mass on a recent Sunday.
“But if you really stop and take a moment to look at history, it’s really a pretty city.”
