"I photograph the master away from the scene to extract his character." -Günther Bauer, photographer
No heels, no steering wheels, no old-fashioned dresses.
Only the essence of the great masters of flamenco, stripped of the concentration that characterizes the interpretation, to look at the relaxed appearance of the man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other, the person.
Two inseparable faces, except in the private, in those moments away from the public, when the intimacy of a gesture, the depth of a stolen look or the expressiveness of the hands, are natural because they do not have to go on stage.
The German Günther Bauer in "Flamenco-People" alternates the theatricality of some shots to singers, dancers and guitarists on stage with the lesser-known side of these masters.
With this lens, the photographer offers an original iconography of flamenco, capturing it from different visual angles.
The exhibition, included in the program of the Month of Flamenco Photography, reflects the international importance of this dance, increasing every day," explains the artist and clarifies that in "Flamenco-People" could also be ordinary people, but seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not the typical images of artists, performers or performers on the scene.
These people portrayed "on the road" are "artists who can convey passion, sadness, joy when they are on stage ... and capture the audience.
To capture the personality of these great it is not necessary to portray them on stage,
because their personality and character are inner.
What interested me was to create an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture with my camera the personality of the greats of flamenco."
With a passion for the festival "Cante de las Minas", Bauer began in 1997 a long journey aimed at portraying singers, guitarists or dancers using a plate camera.
They are portraits that, due to the type of machine and material, resemble classical photography.
The application of different stylistic techniques breaks with the traditional principles of the image, giving the photo modernity, according to an idea that reflects Bauer's conception of flamenco: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and is able to surprise every day."
Not the dance, the singing or the playing in itself, but the personality of the artist, his character, able to conquer the public with his art.
The search for an encounter with the essential elements, with the magic that becomes visible in a certain way of feeling and being, are and have been the constant of this work, on display these days at the El Fotómata gallery.
Famous flamenco artists such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are included in this selection of about seventy portrait artists.
The project has become a kind of anthology of flamenco, and will soon be published in a book that will collect the portraits exhibited on the occasion of the exhibition.
The passion for portraiture led Bauer to repeat the idea two years ago with "Portraits of veteran athletes" ("SportARTproject").
Although in "Flamenco-People" the concept is different, the photographer admits "I love to portray people, to know them and to be able to penetrate for a moment into their lives, whether this is a long or a short moment.
I think portraiture is the most difficult genre in photography.
You meet or confront people, characters you sometimes don’t even know or who give you only a few minutes to take the photo.
Beyond these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to concretize my ideas.”
The collection of contemporary flamenco portraits, entitled "Flamenco-people" is set up at the El Fotómata gallery, at number 20 of via de la Mata, parallel to via Alameda de Hercules, and will be open to the public until next 16 October.
