Carmen Valencia Tortola, Catalan father (Florence Tortola Ferrer) and Andalusian mother (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), was born in the Triana district, and at the age of three moved with the family to London.
She was a free dancer and a specialist in oriental dances.
She led a fascinating life and was a pioneer of female emancipation, such as Isadora Duncan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist and vegetarian, and defended the cause for the abolition of the corset that prevented women from moving freely.
The life of this woman, which marked a revolution in dance and aesthetics in Europe between the two wars, has always fascinated Isabel Bayon.
"I would have liked to work with Pepa Gamboa and she proposed this character to me. I thought it was incredible."
The dancer says: "We do not pretend to tell her whole life, but to collect her spirit.
The titles of his dances suggested some basic elements of flamenco.
So, "the dance of the butterfly" suggested me a guajira, or "the dance of the serpent" some tangos.
Her dance was sensual and I was told that my way of dancing is also part of this aesthetic,” she explains.
The staging includes two exceptional contributions: that of Miguel Poveda, who will sing Isabel again in one of her shows, as she does in "La puerta abierta"; and that of the teacher Matilde Coral, who exceptionally wanted to work with the one who had been her student.
"Matilde plays Tortola as an adult, the character of maturity.
I’m happy because he agreed to work in my work and I feel very honored about that.”
The set-up also includes the musical composition and guitarists such as Jesus Torres and Paco Arriaga, the singing of Miguel Ortega, the Pulga y Moi of Morón; the percussions of El Pájaro, as well as the viola of Rafa La Viola and the collaboration of an actor, Juanfran Juárez "who plays the role of eternal companion of these artists who have always been spa-loves, and in everything.
In some form, the life of this woman is also present, taking place in distant places, especially for that time, such as India, the United States or Russia, and then all of Europe, since she habitually resided in London.
“I wanted to remember her, because I think she is one of the women who had a huge influence in a given historical period and now no one remembers her and even less considers her work as something of value,” says Bayon.
