Talking in sleep
Some children talk at night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the day before, but to those children who talk while staying asleep.
The first time it happens, at most you get a scare, but it doesn’t really matter much.
It is a benign sleep disturbance called somnilochia.
It occurs with some frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely, most of you have been told that you spoke in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in a lifetime, for example associated with an episode of high fever) or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the next day the child no longer remembers anything.
There is no single reason that can explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes they are episodes related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, nighttime fears, nighttime enuresis (peeing in bed), or sleepwalking, but it is not necessarily so.
As already mentioned above it can be associated with stages of very high fever, situations of stress or overexcitation.
In any case, it is a phenomenon still little studied.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It can happen that the person speaks in a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite happens (screams, screams, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be advisable to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to check if there is any issue that is generating an abnormal state of anxiety as an outlet to the situation.
We have said that this is a benign disorder so there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, if coupled with insomnia or stress situation).
What you can do, on the other hand, is take into account a series of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to overexcite the child before he goes to sleep.
Propose quiet games and avoid programs or television series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is tiring to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire a certain inner calm.
This will allow the baby to sleep more peacefully.
Once the sleep apneas appear try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will remember nothing of what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him.
It is useless, because he is not aware of what is happening, and you would interrupt his sleep.
Although he is speaking, he is sleeping and therefore he is resting.
Remember that if it appears very distressed and the episodes have a certain frequency it is best to consult a doctor or check where such a great anxiety in the child comes from.
If you understand what he says (which isn’t the most common situation), don’t be tempted to interrogate him for information.
You will get nothing, because he is asleep and therefore not conscious to organize his thought.
In addition, you are able to hear what it says but not to see what it is dreaming about to say it, so you have to pay close attention to the interpretation of the information and the conclusions to which it could lead.
Never tell the child that you might ask him questions at night to learn his secrets.
Not even a joke.
Such a thing causes enormous anguish.
In short, do not worry, it is nothing serious, it is an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
