The meeting - The blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated yesterday the tenth anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, as Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
Above all, it has regained public confidence, seriously shaken by the infected blood scandal in the years between 1980 and 1990.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
Faced with such a tragedy and protests from the population, the Government of Canada conducted a public inquiry in February 1994, led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent the recurrence of a similar disaster.
While Judge Krever was delaying in drafting a report, some provinces set up a committee with the goal of devising a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Quebec and the Société canadienne du sang (Canadian Blood Society) for all other provinces and the two territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its operations, only 38% of people said they still had confidence in the donation system in Quebec, says Dr. Décary.
The situation was mortifying.
Thanks to continuous efforts to improve the safety of blood samples and to field research over the following years, we have regained the public’s trust,” she explains before proudly stating that by the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the population of Québec now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, is convinced that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases in Europe of the human variant of the mad cow, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, she tells who has been in the presidency since 1998, the year of the foundation.
"And we didn't know at all if that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
It was therefore based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports, according to which when you have doubts and could result in a serious disease, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that manifests itself with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, you take measures of exclusion.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the UK since 1980 was refused.
Now, for a few years, it has been shown that without any doubt this disease is transmitted through infected blood.
This episode showed us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle."
In 1999, a much more efficient technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid (NAT) tests that allow the presence of the virus in the blood of donors to be recognized directly, rather than antibodies against it, on which the tests used until then were based.
TANs have allowed to reduce the window period, that is, from the moment the person contracted the disease to the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
That period could be reduced to less than a week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and therefore not being able to detect them has thus greatly decreased.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
“In other words, that means you’ll need to distribute 12 million blood samples before anyone gets infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood samples each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmitted by transfusion is found.
I believe that today one can feel reassured in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health, says the head of the direction of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than a year ago, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted in the blood by an insect.
We need to be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary before emphasizing that in addition to having secure resources, Héma-Québec must also provide enough.
“The needs are increasing as the population ages.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a supply of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences on the number of donors, which on average constitutes only 3% of Quebecers who are acceptable as donors.
However, all healthy people who are 18 years of age and meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer themselves as donors are not accepted because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where malaria is widespread, they will be rejected for a period equal to one year.
“With this 3%, we can maintain an inventory capable of meeting the needs of hospitals.
Cases of shortage are very rare.
But we need to renew the members of this donor group as they get older and can no longer make donations.
It is now difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Nowadays life is so hectic that it is hardly an hour to donate blood,” says desolate Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, the Héma-Québec distributes not only blood samples, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being deposited at Héma-Québec, which operates the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, there is plenty of blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“We celebrated a few weeks ago the bank entry of our 1,000th sample of cord blood and plan to take more than 1,000 each year.
We should start proposing them for transplants early next year,” says Dr. Décary, who describes this practice of cord blood collection as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they can't access it", as Héma-Québec doesn't have the necessary means to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
