Free Opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Discourse
In the September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from M. Patrick J. Garver, vice president and director of Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, the latter claims that the world’s largest gold company has filed a six-million-dollar defamation lawsuit against three authors and a small, squatter publishing house with the intention of initiating a “transparent public debate.”
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of a defamation lawsuit, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this substantial difference is completely hidden by Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own.
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the writers and publisher of the book Black Canada will have to spend a substantial sum of money in order to organize their defense and fight, with decidedly uneven weapons, against an army of lawyers financed from the practically bottomless pockets of the mining company.
Moreover, in these unequal arms struggles, the tactic is often to ruin the defendant in order to impose a consensual settlement that muzzles the opposition as well as frightens anyone who dares to rule again on the matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it is before the public that it would have to present its own view of the facts.
Contrary to what happens in many countries where Barrick Gold works, in Canada the debates are usually held with the exchange of opinions and not with batons.
It would therefore have been enough for society to open its books, its documents, and establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and the funding of teams of independent researchers who could shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to have too much confidence in the public opinion and badly rejects petitions and letters in support of the authors of Canada Nero.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can ask for a "public" debate when his contempt for that same public is quite evident?
In the vice president's world, it seems that this word refers exclusively to the well-paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; here is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democratic system, even denigrators have the right to speak.
What Barrack Gold doesn’t understand – or doesn’t want to understand – is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Canada Nero does so primarily because it rejects the brutal means adopted by the mining company.
This audience is ready to listen to Barrick and to judge, but on the basis of civil exchanges of opinion, and not from the perspective of what many perceive as a kind of gagging (in search of the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just given the authors of Canada Black an ultimatum instructing them to suspend the use of that word...)
Beyond Garver’s surreal discourse, the Barrack Gold complaint constitutes a direct attack on the freedom of university research and the pursuit of truth, indispensable in any democratic society.
It denies in block the right to cite authentic sources and to debate on facts and interpretations, which represent the very basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to study and discuss topics that are inconvenient to the richest companies in the world, if there are multiple lawsuits, who can do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following the scientific standards as the authors of Canada Nero do.
You have the right to reply.
For a long time, the university environment, of which we are part, has been able to manage debates and disagreements and to resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s excessive measures clearly show that, contrary to its claims, it is not seeking a transparent debate at all.
This is to the detriment of the university world, as is the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to take measures to curb abusive lawsuits.
