Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a committed icon
Blue-eyed beauty was for a long time her ace in her sleeve, for others her weak spot.
Had he got rid of the narcissistic mirror, the American actor from the enchanting smile?
Yes and no.
His discretion, sensitivity and obvious talent would have expelled him from that circle of powerful consecrated to real sacred monsters.
What a constancy.
Paul Newman, who passed away Friday at the age of 83 on his Connecticut ranch from lung cancer, remains one of the last icons of American cinema in recent years.
Less monumental than Brando, to whom he resembled and of whom he was for a long time a sort of rival on the screen, more prudent in his play, certainly more fragile, but also a spokesman for freedom and the development of dramatic convictions.
Mixed couples often have magical children.
He was born in Ohio in 1925, to a German Jewish father and a mother of Hungarian origins.
From these European roots will be born one of the glorious faces of the American dream.
A humble ego, the ultimate mark of quality.
Because he recognized a whole country infatuated with the safe made man, the war fighter of the Pacific, proud in combat, who in the early 50s studied dramatic art at Yale, he subsequently attended the Actor Studio in New York, before triumphing in the theater, on television and soon in the cinema.
The same civil rights activist was also the race car driver who finished second at the 1979 24 Hours of Le Mans, as well as a sex symbol, though part of a 1958 model couple with actress Joanne Woodward.
With him go the shadows of a reserved, discreet, committed star, allergic to the scandals of show business, whose mystery will never be completely unraveled.
An honest man, in the noblest sense of the word.
Paul Newman’s passing this weekend has been a heartbreak for moviegoers as his great characters populate the black screen of memories.
More than half a century of American cinema in full transformation is proposed through his interpretations.
Butch Cassidy's charming cowboy (1969) and that boy unable to desire his fiery wife (Elizabeth Taylor) are confused in memory in The Hot Cat on the Roof, adapted by Tennessee Williams in 1958.
More recently, we remember him as the sensitive Mr. Bridge (1990), troubled by a marriage that did not keep what he promised.
Many more Paul Newmans have gone down in history.
The boxer Rocky Graziano, delinquent, tormented, violent, unforgettable in Up There Someone Loves Me, by Robert Wise, a role intended for James Dean and resumed after his death, which officially launched Newman in 1956.
That cute villain in the excellent Stangata, Oscar for Best Picture in 1973.
A bitter and vengeful billiards player in Robert Rossen's 1961 film The Color of Money by Martin Scorsese, which earned him the only Oscar in 1987 out of nine nominations.
That face through the years, it was hers.
He's back.
Epochs follow each other through his path.
Young people know him best from the cult movie Slap Shot by George Roy Hill (1977), as Reggie Dunlop, coach of an unorthodox ice hockey team.
His fans found him in 1994 in Mr. Hula Hoop, by the Coen brothers.
The circle had closed with a last role as the godfather of the Irish mafia in Era mi padre, in 2003.
Unlike film legends who soon abandoned the trade, Newman will remain in theaters for a long time, denouncing Hollywood in all its splendor, parties and concessions.
Bertrand Tavernier, a French amateur filmmaker, called it, with a hint of irony, "a living challenge to underplay", judging his performances exaggerated.
The profession was not always a game for the handsome Paul Newman, to whom the roles seemed to fall like manna from the sky.
However, he often preferred the role of the marginalized to that of the young actor: neurotic characters, drunken alcoholics or desperate, of which he expressed mischief and rebellion with his perfect traits.
As a director, Newman revealed unknown nuances of his true, pure sensitivity.
Jennifer's 1968 first appearance (based on the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), with his wife Joanne Woodward in the lead role, drew a subtle female portrayal of melancholy.
He, who lost his son Scott to an overdose, dedicated in 1984 the film Harry and Son, discreet and sad.
Among the countless tributes that rained yesterday on Newman, his great friend and old partner Robert Redford (they had starred together in La Stangata and Butch Cassidy) stated with infinite sadness, "His presence has made my life and this country better."
Generosity and love for life, two great characteristics of the deceased actor.
Beyond a legendary career, a great activist for civil rights, ecology, independent cinema, a protester of the Hollywood drift, is thus extinguished.
We will have seen her face stand out on bottles of vinegar, sauces, cookies and other foods, judging it a choice of bad taste, although born as a gag.
The proceeds from those sales were, however, earmarked for his Struggling Children's Foundation.
Newman, instead of resting on his myth, chose to commit himself to the end.
He left his five daughters a letter that said "Always and to the end, your father was incredibly grateful to his good star.
To be there was a privilege.”
And just as privileged was it for us to follow the path of such a clear and generous American artist.
Model citizen, therefore, and much more.
What was produced in the invoice factory of Zuschlag & partners?
The hearing of the criminal trial against János Zuschlag et al. will be held shortly on 8 October.
The politician and his associates are charged with repeated commercial fraud committed within the framework of a criminal association that has caused considerable damage, and other crimes, including forgery of documents.
According to the Prosecutor's Office, the money obtained from calls for tenders was used by them for private purposes, and they often certified the carrying out of the activities by means of false invoices.
The state and municipal money, in total 65 million florins, ended up partly in the coffers of the organization Fiatal Baloldal, partly in the pockets of some people.
According to the method disclosed by the investigating authorities, they have withdrawn the money obtained from calls for tenders on the basis of invoices for non-existent transactions and the associations have never fulfilled their obligations.
According to the indictment, most of the invoices were false.
To make them, the blocks of invoices were purchased at the market in Józsefváros, while the circular stamps were manufactured in Kiskunhalas.
And to decide on behalf of which firms to issue invoices, it was established among other things during the trip between the hills above the Balaton where János Zuschlag had sent István Lados.
According to the latter's confession he had to choose pensions and restaurants.
He asked for an invoice for consumption, on the model of these then invoices were prepared to be forwarded to the competition notices, among others, to those of the Ministry for Youth and Sport, the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs and the Municipality of Budapest.
Most of these are the work of István Lados and András <0xC5><0x90>ri, who, according to our information, mainly prepared the reports necessary to obtain the funding.
