The Psychology of Excess Bidding: Why Spend More Money?
At auctions, buyers are likely to spend more, to overvalue the goods.
Neuroscientists and economists at New York University have managed to uncover the neuro-economic underpinnings of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, men do not want to be left behind in a race such as the eBay auction, so they are available to pay even a higher price.
The research sought to trace the nervous pattern of this “game” at the nervous system level through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, the other group of players participated in an auction while using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method they examined the active areas of the brain of the people participating in the experiment.
In both games participants could win money, but in the auction game, where the substantial element is to bid more than the other, the striated body under the cerebral cortex enters intensively into operation when you lose to the game.
This brain area, in addition to other functions, plays a role in the "self-gratification" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the price increase is explained by avoiding the vehement reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, the research team's economists conducted a financial tracking survey.
In this investigation, three groups tendered against a partner under different conditions.
The control group reported what the real value of the product in question was and they made their bet.
To another group besides this they have promised that in the case of winning they will receive another prize of $ 15.
The third group would have received $15 before the auction, but the members of the group would have lost the money in case of loss at the auction.
The difference between the two groups was that for one of them the win was emphasized, while for the other the loss.
By checking the neurologists' hypothesis, the members of the group that played "against loss" were willing to make higher bets than the control or "winner" group.
“These results are not deducible from any of the previously existing economic theories.
In fact, until now they explained the phenomena found at auctions with the joy of winning and avoiding risk.
Only the methods of creating the neurological image helped to resolve the contradiction between the two theories, so we came up with a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor in the School of Economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: when to go to the doctor?
Nearly half a billion people in the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while chronic liver disease is one of the leading causes of death in Hungary.
In Hungary, the number of hepatitis patients amounts to one hundred thousand, of which only 7,000 are treated: the reason is that many patients do not know that they are infected.
The definition of hepatitis is the collective name of contagious liver diseases caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between the symptoms, typical are hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and diseases caused differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the food channel (e.g. water and infected food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal discharge, saliva).
For those who travel it is useful to vaccinate against the virus A and B, against C there is no vaccine.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after the consumption of infected foods, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After yellowish spots form on the skin and white of the eyes, stools become light and urine dark, healing takes place within two to three weeks.
A million people die each year worldwide from hepatitis B, the most severe variant of the disease, which causes liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason is, according to estimates, that only one in ten people receive a drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated it can cause liver cirrhosis and liver cancers.
Most infected people do not know that they have contracted the disease because the pathogens subtly destroy the liver cells, in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, it is very important to prevent and carry out regular medical tests.
This disease is much more common than the average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed.
In the world today, the number of people infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus amounts to 200 million.
Since even a routine laboratory examination reveals the disease, it is worth consulting the family doctor when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
Recognized in time the disease is curable, the virus can be eliminated from the body, thus ceases the infectious power and can be prevented the formation of tumors.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, first organized in 2004 worldwide by associations of patients.
The aim is to draw attention to chronic viral hepatitis, the causes of its development and early recognition of the disease.
Who believes in God feels less pain?
According to the result of a recent survey, the religious faith functions as a kind of analgesic that has made the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
Scientists at the University of Oxford have carried out an interesting experiment, examining how faith in God affects the sensation of pain, the British Telegraph reported.
As part of the rather bizarre investigation, an electroshock was carried out on 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists, while all were observing a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to reject much of the pain.
Thanks to the exploration technique of the human brain, it was discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of the brain responsible for controlling pain.
The test is the first in a series of researches in which, in addition to academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians of the University take part.
The test took place exactly like this: an instrument that emits discharges and passes the electroshock was connected to the left hand of the subject of the experiment.
The researchers asked participants to focus on two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted in the 17th century by Sassoferrato and the Lady with the Hermelin by Leonardo da Vinci painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the examination hoped that the image of the Virgin Mary would give rise to a sort of religious state among believers, while Leonardo's painting was chosen because it did not differ too much from the other and they considered it to have a reassuring effect.
The subjects of the experiment spent half an hour in front of the MRI scanner and in this time frame they received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive series, while observing either the religious-themed painting or the other.
Catholics reported that the vision of the Virgin Mary made them feel "safe", as if "someone took care" of them and "they calmed down and were pervaded by peace".
Looking at the religious-themed image, they realized 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo’s work in front of them.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who took part in the test himself, believes that such a result can be achieved with any image with a strong effect even for atheists, but you have to find the right image.
“We have to look for an image to which they have very positive feelings, like a mother or a father,” he said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the result of the research.
"The practice of faith should change, and in many cases it can change our personality," Wright added.
After the excellent results remains only the question whether the painting of a Madonna of Leonardo or another painter of similar caliber is presented to the believers, what effect could it have on the control of pain?
Would the vision of a quality Virgin Mary bring better results?
You are what you say about yourself
On the 10th birthday, Google can claim to be in people’s pockets as well as in the sky above their heads; it knows where they spent their holidays, which clinic they go to and what interests them.
This, however, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company’s directors, is not yet enough.
As for the skeptics who make a comparison with the Orwellian nightmare, they don’t really see the substance of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google’s main purpose is to collect as much personal data of its users as possible and this is necessary to meet the original goal of Google’s founders that was: “we put all the information of the world into one system!”
According to the director of Google interviewed the company, after 10 years of revolutionary work, it is still at the beginning of being able to manage all the information.
Asked what will happen five years from now, Schmidt said: “Would he like Google to answer questions like ‘what do I do tomorrow?’ or ‘what would be the right job for me?’ but software doesn’t know how to answer seemingly simple questions because it doesn’t know enough about users.”
Not all Internet users are aware that during their searches on the Internet exactly the words searched are recorded, from which IP address they are searched and on which page the interested parties stop after the search.
Through the Personalized Search launched two years ago users can e.g. memorize their browsing history, they can relate to what they have searched and clicked, these then in the long run will generate much better tailor-made results; on this same logic is based Recommendations with which the system offers us products and services based on our previously declared and registered preferences.
What happens if my data is used against me, if they look at what I do? - users worried about Google's data monopoly ask.
In most cases the counter-reactions of Internet users are provoked by the fear felt for the size of the potential power represented by the company, and not for the guilt, for the fear of punishment, for the desire for freedom or even for the rebellion to power.
However, one fact is confirmed, namely that all the searched expressions are not only recorded but in reasoned cases can also be provided to third parties, in such legal cases nothing defends the personal rights of Internet users.
Perhaps the most striking example of this in recent times has been the coordinated action against pedophiles in Brazil, in which Google forwarded to the Brazilian government the information that made it possible to identify pedophiles from the Orkut community page maintained by Google.
Internet users concerned about personal rights, on the other hand, sighed of relief in May when the company – in agreement with the EFF e-legal protection association – successfully proved the truth in court against the FBI: even then you can not force Google with any point of the constitution to provide any information requested secretly by the FBI.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully ripped out nearly 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search expressions obtained in reference to the confirmation of the child protection law passed years earlier, but still failed to get individual users’ search lists and the entire list of web pages and keywords dating back two months.)
Google’s judgment is therefore rather contradictory: those who are afraid to provide their personal data scourge Google because they believe that in this way their intimate sphere and private life is affected by starting to use its services and they rise with the rebellion due to the multinationals that stand out for the conservative image.
Meanwhile, American geek culture and the proliferation of enthusiasts, activists and computer users appearing in numerous countries see in them the future generation of big companies, the "cool corporation", unlike their rival, Microsoft liquidated as the conqueror of the world because of Windows, although both fight for the same goal.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for an identification code, does not ask for money for its services, the source code is kept up-to-date and the package of programs is much more accessible, youthful and cool than the official practice of the software giant.
But it can also happen because geeks see exactly the problematic relationship between personal rights and the internet, which implies one of the most repeated keywords in recent years, web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is all about collaboration, about intentionally leaving traces behind us and exploiting the communication channels at our disposal and while the size of these changes for each individual, the substance is the same: to show ourselves.
An average young person can create profiles in multiple community pages, from Facebook to Xanga, can link them with other services such as Twitter or last.fm that lists his musical tastes, all of these can be placed in systems such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, can also write blogs on which automatically appear his most recent photo galleries stored on Flickr or on Picasa.
Meanwhile we read of numerous exemplary cases from which it is clear that the girl, seeing the series of photos taken in the morning by the joint tour of friends, easily comes to know who spent the night with her perfidious boyfriend or a company can fire an employee because he wrote a sincere opinion on the company's top: one thing is for sure, the concept of private life has now completely reconsidered.
Those who live an online life make sure to show themselves and so we can formulate the fundamental thesis that hides behind the behavior of young people.
Those who want to hide something or just want to avoid the monopoly of Google can do so (beginning for example with Scroogle using the Google search system but at the same time does not voluntarily leave traces).
There are many people who do not register on community pages to not be found, Google's online applications, from text processing to image management and news collection, can be replaced with alternative versions not linked to huge server parks and that do not make up our best profile so far existing.
The public does not even secretly wait for the moment when Google will pull out the claws.
Currently the company with its 156 billion dollars in value is worth more than IBM (140 billion dollars), Intel (124 billion dollars) or Coca Cola (110 billion dollars), AdWords/AdSense advertising spaces threaten the revenues of advertising agencies, the services introduced in record time instead cause great discomfort not only to Microsoft but also to numerous companies of software development.
However, the critical observers next to all this find alarming points: the company top for example has totally rejected the protest of employees after having doubled the rate of corporate asylum, has considered too expensive the repeated daily catering of employees, but all this diminishes the fact that in 2006 Google has bowed the head to the Chinese government and in accordance with their agreement will offer all the good results.
An internal rule of the company seems to be not to advertise a new service in advance but only when it will be usable, one thing is sure, however, that the foreseeable problems of the coming months and years will move the world in one point: while some believe that the project of scanning and archiving of books and magazines of Google will assume such proportions that the company will soon find itself in front of the US Supreme Court Health system, others are afraid.
The fact that Google is building a genetic data base can offer good material to the next generation of science fiction writers, the story Scroogled by the famous Cory Doctorow describes the future with Orwellian accents, in which a man with Google data can be approached in an alarming way.
