The intelligent machine imitates the flight of the hornet
What could be the best method to develop anti-collision technologies if not to mimic obstacle sensors found in nature?
For example, those of bees.
In the surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the hornets gave the initial strategic cue to Nissan engineers on how to build the next generation of anti-collision systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the biomimetic robot BR23C, a robotic mini-car with bee properties, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can avoid all collisions.
Flying bees form their own oval personal space that really looks a lot like our protective shield - explained to the exhibition Kazuhiro Doi, director of PR technologies and research and development.
Important is the role of the view of the bee, capable of a view of 300 degrees in any direction.
The engineers drew on the telemetric laser idea to copy the function of the bee's sight.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two meters away within a 180-degree radius, calculates the distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor that immediately turns it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second, the robot senses the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels as necessary to avoid the accident.
This avoidance maneuver, differently from the present system, takes place instinctively.
“If this were not the case, the car robot would not be able to react quickly to avoid collisions,” says Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Lab and the robot car project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the damaged and innermost layer of the protective shield, within which collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process has to reflect what a bee does to avoid the other bees.
This process must take place in the blink of an eye.
But unlike bees the deviation cannot go up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the direction of steerability of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities available to bees to avoid the other bees, the robot, as a possibility available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and have a high energy density, which means that they last longer than lithium ion batteries.
According to Andoh it is important the instantaneity of the intelligent reaction, not the processing of the data or even less the ability to store them.
This robot has to process some inputs in a few seconds and react.
There is no need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuvering data, so it only uses a memory of a few tens of Kb.
You don’t need a gigabyte or megabyte memory.
This is the first step towards the development of a technology for the immediate avoidance of collisions, which, according to Nissan, can be installed on production vehicles within 10 years.
A further possibility of application can be represented by the unification with the GPS satellite navigation system that avoiding obstacles on the road leads to the destination.
