The written version of the $700 billion bailout law was drafted for the purchase of disproportionate credits, to be applied in several parts.
In the first step, half of the amount is spent.
In the new deal, which lasted until midnight on Saturday, the leaders of the congress decided on the $700 billion bailout after a debate that lasted for days, Reuters reported.
"We have made some serious progress," said Nancy Pelosi, Democratic Speaker of the House of Representatives, who said it was only a matter of putting the deal on paper.
Both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain, supported the compromise plan.
Treasury Minister Henry Paulson, speaking about the outcome of the compromise, said: the program will work and be effective, but there is still a lot to be done. According to Pelosi it is not about the bailout of Wall Street but the reversal of the economic chariot.
The written version of the plan was made public before the opening of Asian markets at 8 a.m. Washington time (02 p.m. on Monday according to Central European time), but it did not bring a large growth of the stock exchanges.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will first vote on the bill called the Economic Stabilization Act of 2008 concerning the program, after which it will fall to the Senate.
President George W. Bush spoke with Pelosi on Saturday evening, then welcomed the news of the deal to the White House.
"We are pleased with the progress made tonight and greatly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and defend the economy," White House spokesman Tony Fratto said in a statement.
The program, however, differs from the Bush administration’s original proposal that the $700 billion would all be spent on buying the bonds with disproportionate credits behind them.
Now, as a first step, you can spend at most half of the sum of $700 billion, $250 billion immediately after the congressional vote on Monday, with these the Treasury will buy securities with disproportionate credits behind, the fate of the remaining $100 billion will be decided by the president.
A special college will oversee the program in which the president of the Federal Reserve also participates.
Spending the other half of the $700 billion depends on a new Congressional decree.
Under the law, the Treasury can apply a combined tactic: it can buy credits, mortgages and securities at the same time with mortgages and other types of "poisoned" credits.
The purchase can take place through auctions and in a direct way - they announced competent of the ministry.
The legal norm makes it possible for the companies concerned to take part in an insurance program where the Treasury guarantees the means that give concern, for which the companies will pay a price appropriate to the probable damages.
Henrz Paulson said: The law gives the necessary means for $700 billion to arrive for the urgent needs of the American monetary system, whether it is the purchase of the wrong financial means, or their insurance, or to avoid the risk of the collapse of a large financial institution.
We will take all necessary steps to be ready to introduce the newly signed law.
The directors of the banks in crisis and waiting for state aid think instead that the government will limit their exit, defined by the overseas slang simply as gold parachutes.
Payment limitations will only occur in some cases, furthermore the limitations depend on how the Treasury will offer the aid.
In essence, the limitation means that if the ministry buys as part of an auction, it will impose a surcharge on the gold parachute, if they do not send the fallen bank manager to retirement.
At the time of direct purchase of the disproportionate loans, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that the money of the directors is not exaggerated.
To this it should be added that the existing gold parachute contracts will not change, the limitation is valid only for new ones to incentivize participation in the program.
"This is the first case in American history of the coming into force of a legal limitation on the remuneration of directors-general," said Democrat Barney Frank, chairman of the House Financial Services Committee.
In addition, the state has the right to appropriate a share of the banks participating in the program, reducing the risk of taxpayers, since in the end they can also earn if the economy, and with it the bank rescued, will get back on its feet.
The bill includes that in the next five years the president must submit to Congress a proposal that provides for how to reimburse taxpayers for anticipated losses arising from the financial sector.
Of course, on both sides there were those who expressed their doubts about the project.
That’s not what American citizens have asked us not to defend taxpayer dollars,” said California Republican Rep. Darrell Issa.
