Jaróka: We must break the vicious circle of poverty and segregation
The European Summit for Equal Opportunities began today in Paris, organized this year by France with the rotating presidency of the European Union.
Livia Járóka, Fidesz deputy of the European People's Party in the message addressed to the plenary as the main speaker of the congress, drew attention to school segregation because it is the most serious legal violation affecting Roma children and the most serious obstacle to their affirmation.
Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs, on behalf of the French Presidency, and Vladimír <0xC5><0xA0>pidla, European Commissioner responsible for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities, opened the conference at the highest level.
Among those invited to the conference were governments, European social partners and representatives of major European civil and rights organisations in the field of equal opportunities.
Járóka, according to the press office of the Fidesz PE parliamentary group, recalled, in addition to discrimination in recruitment, that Roma are being excluded from the labour market primarily because of their low schooling.
"The majority of young Roma have no middle-level education and as a result of poor quality primary education only a trivial number of them can achieve a higher education degree."
Mr Járóka also stressed, as a fundamental human right, the key role of education in enforcing human rights.
Investing in the education of Roma children can mean strengthening the economy of the member states of the European Union.
According to the MEP, it is necessary to raise awareness of these links among Roma and non-Roma in the broader context.
In fact, the sooner a Roma starts school, the greater their chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market; through taxes paid for income and consumption they contribute to the nation’s budget.
"The right of Roma to European citizenship must guarantee their right to quality education and the elimination of low-level and segregated schools," said Lívia Járóka.
According to the deputy, the union of purpose and action of the European Union is necessary to speed up the processes of desegregation of schools and for this reason it is of fundamental importance to respect the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives.
"The vicious cycle of poverty, segregation and unemployment must be broken, Roma children must be given the opportunities afforded by the democratic space so that they can contribute as full citizens to the future of Europe" - asked Járóka.
In the sign of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities" to be guaranteed for all, the purpose of the European Summit for Equal Opportunities organized every year since last year's meeting in Berlin is to ensure a single forum to promote the objectives of anti-discrimination and equal opportunities set at state and European level.
