Accidents work, Napolitano: "Critical prevention"
Every day, in Italy, 2,500 accidents occur at work, 3 people die and 27 remain permanently disabled.
For 2007, the INAIL data confirm that white deaths were about 1,200.
Figures that testify to the severity of a phenomenon that remains one of the main causes of death and causes almost twice as many deaths as murders.
To draw the attention of institutions, social forces and the media to this dramatic issue, today Anmil celebrates in all the provinces of Italy the 58th National Day for the victims of accidents at work, institutionalized on the second Sunday of October.
"The worrying data released by Anmil and the tragic reports of these days confirm how crucial is the issue of prevention at work," says the President of the Republic Giorgio Napolitano, in the message sent to the president of Anmil, National Association of Mutilated and Disabled Workers, Pietro Mercandelli.
The Head of State expresses his "strong appreciation for the constant associative commitment in favor of prevention in the workplace, the protection of injured workers, the assistance of the families of the victims and the awareness of public opinion".
“Of course, an indignant ‘enough’ has arisen, sincerely shared, in the face of tragedies that, because of their size, arouse the clamor of the media and the involvement of public opinion, but daily reality again proposes dramatic cases, even repetitive in their dynamics.”
Napolitano does not hide that "there is undoubtedly also a problem of resources: it is decisive to invest in training and information.
The numerous initiatives promoted in the school environment for a more direct awareness by young people who come to the world of work take on particular significance.
It is necessary to keep the attention to the phenomenon alive, not to give up on the alarm about its social gravity, to apply and improve the legislative norms.
For his part, the president of the Chamber Gianfranco Fini stressed "how the phenomenon of white deaths constitutes an absolute social emergency, which offends the conscience of each of us and imposes on all institutions a decisive commitment to urgently put an end to it".
"The data on accidents at work seem to indicate a slight positive trend, but this does not mean that the number of white deaths is still impressive," said the president of Anmil Pietro Mercandelli.
In fact, we would not want this “downward trend” to translate into less attention, because it is precisely when attention is relaxed that tragedy explodes.
"We believe that too little is still being done at a general level to counteract the phenomenon of accidents and the contrast can be exercised through multiple actions.
They are necessary, in our opinion - Mercandelli has emphasized - more controls and inspections, but also a stronger intervention on the training of the workers, and this from the world of the school".
"An additional effort is needed - he added - with regard to communication and public awareness.
But above all, there needs to be a greater sense of responsibility on the part of employers towards a phenomenon that represents a social emergency.”
Mercandelli then denounced "the progressive deterioration of the levels of compensation protection provided for victims of work" and "the welfare drift towards which the system is pushing in recent years".
"The objective is therefore to return to the worker the insurance guarantee - he added - so that the fate of those who are injured should not depend on spontaneity or granting from time to time ordered by the legislator."
MP3 Players Are At Risk of Hearing
Listening to high-volume music for an extended period of time using portable music devices such as MP3 players can cause permanent hearing injuries.
In a statement released in Brussels, the European Commission cited the opinion of the EU’s Scientific Committee on Emerging and Newly Identified Health Risks (Csrseri) published today.
“From this scientific opinion, it emerges that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable music devices weekly for more than an hour a day holding the device at a high volume are at risk of permanent hearing loss.”
“I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and cell phones at high acoustic levels may unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably,” says Meglena Kuneva.
“The scientific findings reveal a clear risk and we must react quickly.
Most importantly, we need to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We also need to review existing control systems in the light of this scientific opinion to ensure that they are fully effective and keep pace with the new technology."
Brussels had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the large use of portable music devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they cause.
"Scientists confirm that there is cause for concern and the European Commission will now discuss with Member States and stakeholders what measures could be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable music devices and similar equipment."
Currently, there is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music equipment to 100 dB, but there are growing concerns about hearing damage that can result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
You can greatly limit this damage by resorting to solutions such as reducing levels and duration of noise exposure.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee points out that users of portable music equipment if they listen to music at high volume (more than 89 decibels) for only 5 hours a week exceed the limits currently in force regarding the maximum noise allowed in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods are at risk of permanent hearing loss after a period of 5 years.
This would affect 5-10% of the users of such devices and their number can be quantified between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
