Elites in Danger
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago with the vote of the House of Representatives against the bailout of $ 700 billion launched by the White House: a significant part of Americans was, and is, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
Yesterday’s New York Times confirms this by informing us that the ongoing crisis is splitting the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast, moderate, favorable to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, instead, conservative, hostile to the “those of Washington” and to the world of finance, strong especially in the Central and Southern States.
The soul, in fact, which became prepotently alive with the vow of which I said at the beginning.
However, this is only one example of the changes, of the great changes, which the current economic earthquake may foretell or already reveal: not only in the United States but throughout the West and perhaps not here alone.
Both in the United States and in Europe the crisis seems to work as an accelerator of phenomena in incubation for a long time that in the new climate solidify and finally come to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary revival, of the double category State-sovereignty in relation to a sort of re-nationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions which have, yes, close ties with foreign countries, but which first and foremost see involved to a very large extent the budgets of people and families living in one country, in one state.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and families who, by the way, are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems essentially out of the question or not to have much to say: the clearest proof is given by the European Union, which, as usual, divides between different interests and between different state strategies fails to decide any common political line.
And so it is from the government of each individual state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and revival plans, new rules, and above all the disbursement of funds: since when you get to the narrow are only the states that own the economic resources, the mass of financial resources able to try to put things back on track.
And they also possess the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, in certain circumstances, which probably no market or international organization will ever have to a similar extent.
This new emphasis that the crisis places on the state-national element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the increasing importance that the most recent developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor very closely linked to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, of increasingly sophisticated technology, of the immaterial, while we were convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we suddenly realized that our future will have to cope to an increasing extent with those very little immaterial things that are water, crops, oil.
All things that, look a little, can certainly be transported from one place to another of the earth but are still absolutely linked to a limited space, to a territory.
So that the one who finds himself sovereign, certainly possesses several more cards than the one who is not, to the one who has the misfortune to live in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
I come to the second novelty which, however, foreshadows a fracture.
Whoever says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand the awareness of the objective need for authoritative leadership, the demand for someone who knows how to take charge of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for the existing leaderships, economic species, proved so inadequate and full of shadow zones.
And at the same time something even deeper and in a certain sense disturbing: a discredit, an intolerance, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in a growing number of Western countries.
That is to say, the conviction that before their actions are the same ideas as the social elites so far on the rise, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the overall sense of the term, has made its own time and is increasingly alien to the opinions of the majorities, seems to be gaining ground in vast sectors of the population.
The demand for American leadership, in short, underground feeds a ramified but powerful movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and of the traditional political structures, which manifests itself in the sudden electoral "revolts" or in the sudden turns of the collective moods of these last and very last times, from the conservative rise in Austria-Bavaria to the collapse of the Granbell consensus in Italy.
One has the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats, someone would say, are finding it increasingly difficult to understand, and therefore to represent, what is not now taking shape in the deeper strata of Western societies and which the economic crisis is reinvigorating, increasing, potentially agitating.
In the face of all this, to speak of a "rebellion of the masses" on the agenda would be frankly exaggerated.
But keeping your eyes wide open certainly isn’t.
The super glue for walking on walls
Defeat the laws of gravity thanks to a super glue and in the future walk on the walls like Spiderman.
It is the target of several American research centers and now a team of four institutes has come very close to it.
With a sticker measuring just 2.5 square centimetres, the researchers were able to hold a 100-kilogram body glued to a vertical wall.
The American journal Science has published the findings of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the team is an evolution of existing ones using a particular carbon structure, called carbon nanotubes.
“The principle of glue can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged like a stack of spaghetti,” explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists were inspired by the legs of geckos, covered with microscopic hairs that manage to ensure a perfect grip on the animal.
Tests conducted on different materials, such as glass, Teflon and sandpaper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles and at the same time "detaches easily from the wall," explains Liming Dai, a researcher in the Faculty of Engineering at the University of Dayton.
WALKING ON WALLS? -"This material could be useful as a transient adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
Maybe to walk on walls just like Spiderman? Maybe so, but researchers think of a much less fascinating use as the connection between electronic devices, because carbon nanotubes are conductors of heat and electric current.
Other applications may relate to aerospace engineering.
No superheroes at the moment.
