Students victims of expensive-rents up to 900 euros for a room
The rent market for university students knows no crisis.
According to the latest survey by Sunia, the tenants' union, taking a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now taken on very serious character to the point of excluding entire bands of young people from the right to study for the very high overall costs that families of origin should bear - explains the head of the office of studies of Sunia, Laura Mariani - in these cities the strong demand from students has so distorted the market that it triggers a process of generalized increase also for residents ".
In most cases, the lease offers also contain a number of violations: free type contracts, unregistered, without limit of fees, sub-rents linked.
For the Sunia, extraordinary interventions are needed that, through the revision of taxation, can calm prices.
Looking at the detail of the survey, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, you need about 450 euros; for a single room you go from a minimum of 650 (Black Bands area) to an average value of 800 (Lambiate area, Udine and Fair) to a maximum of 900 (in the Vittoria area).
In Florence a bed costs on average 350/400 euros, a room about 700.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in the areas close to the University, you need 250/280 euros for a bed in a double, from 370 to 500 for a single.
In Rome in areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna) are asked about 600 euros for a single room, 450 for a bed in a double.
Values only slightly lower (550 euros for a single room) in areas close to other Universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
You save only if you move to peripheral areas: 300 euros for a bed and 450 a single in Prenestina, Centocelle and similar areas.
In Naples for a bed you need 300/450 euros, for a room you spend from 400 to 600 euros, with the highest prices in the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei areas.
In Bari for a bed you need 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a single.
In smaller cities prices are lower in absolute terms, but they have a greater weight in the city economy.
In the cities where the phenomenon of rents to non-EU students is more frequent, as in Perugia, there is finally another anomaly: the increase of about 25/30% of the fee charged to foreign students compared to that applied to Italians.
Farewell old cinema Paradise, the cities cancel the historic rooms
Historic movie theaters close in favor of multiplexes.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, it is like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in the large Italian urban centers but also in the cities of the province.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth on the periphery of the large multi-sales and the consequent death by consumption of mono-sales in the central areas of the cities, is one of those events that seem inescapable and incontrovertible but also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
Often disappearing are historical places and loads of memory, "it is as if a friend, an acquaintance with whom we have shared a piece of the road and many emotions," observes the director of Nuovo cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago earned Tornatore the Oscar and the Grand Prix of the Cannes jury, and that told the poetry of a provincial room and the nostalgia for a way of living perhaps always lost cinema
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of retailers, speak clearly: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and the biggest hit is paid by the cinemas in the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures is Emilia-Romagna with 82 cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And as proof that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, these are the three Italian regions that have registered the largest number of new multi-screen cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exercise has developed irrationally," observes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "it is useful that new structures are built but it would be necessary to guarantee the survival of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its visitors are willing to move into multiplexes.
Not to mention the lack of allocation for the fund in favor of the merchants: the debt receivable of the State is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful, from an ethical and moral point of view, that the Government does not respect the existing laws.
To support the sector would need between 16 and 18 million euros per year.
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about closures, decided to run for cover with the signing of a protocol between the Municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to protect and promote single-screen cinemas both in the historic center and on the outskirts.
Among the rules provided are tax relief measures for operators and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic zone and will have special rates for the stop and in some parking lots.
"It is an initiative that I like" observes Giuseppe Tornatore"and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by putting in place other measures.
It is certain, however, that to counter the overpowering of multiplexes, traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema di Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to do "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass in front of the Rialto or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale now closed, where I have experienced many shared emotions, not to see the billboards blackened by dust I turn to the other side.
Links between politics and 'ndrangheta arrested mayor of Gioia Tauro
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was willing to standardize the choices of the Municipality to the interests of the cosca Piromalli".
There are heavy accusations that the magistrates of the Anti-Mafia Directorate of Calabria address to the mayor and deputy mayor of Gioia Tauro Giorgio Dal Torrione and Rosario Schiavone, and to the mayor of Rosarno Carlo Martelli, arrested this morning for external competition in a mafia association.
In handcuffs also Gioacchino Piromalli, the elderly mediator between the clan and public administrations, and his nephew lawyer, namesake of the boss, already convicted of association for mafia criminal, sentenced to compensate 10 million euros.
"In defiance of any legal and moral norm, as well as common sense," the prosecutors write, the two local administrations had expressed their willingness to pay advice to lawyer Piromalli.
"It would have been thus allowed to the cosca - write the judges - to enter officially inside the municipalities facilitating the possibilities, already enormous, of control and address of the public administration".
The president of the Calabrian regional junta, Agazio Loiero, does not hide that "collusions between local authorities and organized crime" exist in his region: "There are areas where the mafia intensity is stronger than in others, where collusion is almost inevitable.
But there are many local politicians who resist the pressure of the 'ndrangheta, heroes who keep themselves clean."
The arrests this morning follow those of last July with which the police announced that they had decapitated the Pyromalli thigh.
Since the end of last April, the municipal council of Gioia Tauro was dissolved but already in 1991, and always due to alleged conditioning between organized crime and local administration, local politicians had been relieved of the task of administering the Municipality.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, mayor of the UDC at the time of the dissolution, had been elected head of a center-right coalition, after the May 2006 ballot.
He shouted at the scandal when the Prefecture ordered the dissolution of the city council.
He called in the then deputy minister of the Interior Marco Minniti, accusing him of having designed the whole thing for a political issue, but the judges, in the arrest order signed this morning, explain that the piromalli cosca had even come to ask for the variation of the project of the A3.
From the environmental interceptions ordered against Dal Torrione, write the pm, emerged "the willingness to marry the needs of an entrepreneur, representative of a larger group notoriously close to the Pyromalli, uniformizing the choices of the public administration to the interests of the cosca".
When the energy is born from the waves now the big ones come into the field
It is an exterminated field, occupying more than 70% of the planet’s surface and is now being discovered by the world’s major energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources they’ve set their sights on, and now they’re trying to get their hands on, giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of harnessing marine energy was put aside, but now environmentalist demands and the new rise in oil are giving momentum to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 per cent of the world’s electricity needs could be covered by swell systems.
This would be twice the amount currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, there would be currents and tides.
Colossi on the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a plant in Northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years later, betting on marine energy is becoming more and more and among these companies have always been devoted to traditional energy.
“Chevron is studying ocean energy technologies,” a spokesperson for a company affiliated with the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, “and is considering cooperating with us.”
The cooperation in question concerns obtaining a permit from the U.S. Energy Commission, necessary to start a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
This is a sign, especially considering that the US continues to extract oil in Alaska, and President Bush recently launched a plan for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, there are Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey to travel the road of energy that comes from the sea and the sums invested so far, although not known in detail, indicate, according to observers, an interest on the rise.
Technology to be developed.
Experts speak of a technology still in its infancy, also because marine energy does not escape all doubts about the environmental impact.
For now, plants like the one in Portugal or some in Scotland are small in size and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, however, technologies with a greater environmental impact must be used.
And the choices are different: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The thrust of the waves, which causes the buoys to move up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure by pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure turns a turbine which in turn powers a generator.
Electricity is sent to shore through submarine cables.
For now there are four such plants under design, pending federal approval only, and some of the energy could be used for a military installation.
Verdant Power, meanwhile, already produces power for a mall and parking lot using six underwater turbines in New York’s East River.
The movement of water when there are tides rotates the turbine blades, creating a rotary movement that powers a generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to take advantage of the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say to the Institute for Electricity Research, deserves at this time the potential of the tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It is on tidal energy that states like New York, Maine, and Alaska, along with others on the coast, have already invested $7.5 million in 2008 and planned up to $35 million in 2009.
